New Orleans spent decades paving over swampland to bring its people into the 20th century. But as the fallout from Hurricane Katrina made clear, the very infrastructure that modernized the city works against it when disaster strikes. That’s why local architects and advocates have put forth the Greater New Orleans Urban Water Plan, a $6.2 billion effort to give city a 21st-century water management strategy that borrows from, for instance, the Dutch. Reporter Sarah Goodyear asks whether rain gardens, detention ponds, bioswales, porous pavement and the like represent the way forward for a perennially cash-strapped and tradition-bound New Orleans.

resume: I believe in truth, justice, and that the American way can be more than just the short-term pursuit of increasing profits. I believe our pursuit of happiness should be investment in ourselves and in our understanding of each other and the world around us.

I am classically trained in architecture and city planning but became a self-taught web developer because of supportive parents, peers, and the employers who took a chance on a person who wanted more out of life than a day job. As a result, I tend to work in small teams and wear a lot of hats. I look good in hats.

I strive to make the world a better place, and if it helps you understand why, it's because I selfishly want to live in a better world. The problem is that the real estate market on worlds is pretty constrained right now so it's important to try and make decisions that are supportive of all seven billion of your roommates.

“Think globally, act locally” might be pretty overused but I think it's best to concentrate on the smaller community you're a part of and make an impact there. That way you don't spread yourself too thin with all of the things you can't possibly get to, but concentrate on what and who you know.
